I have learned recently that this is very common for people with adhd, and I’m not just lazy. Honestly, that sentence describes most things in my life right now. *sigh*

For context, for the last 10+ years I will miss breakfast and completely skip lunch and instead having random food at random times until dinner. Because dinner is a meal I share with my family, it helps keep that mealtime regulated. When left on my own, i’m basically feral.

So on a whim I set alarms on my phone  to remind me to eat at meal/snack times, thinking it was silly but I’d give it a try. 3 days in and every time one goes off I’m like “oh look at that! I had no idea so much time had gone by!” This little whim experiment is HELPING, y’all.

But if we had continued to push and push...I don’t think he would have that bravery, and he definitely wouldn’t have a stress free relationship with food. It was scary when he was younger, following his lead with his food, but I’m so glad I did.

We’ve found ways to make sure he’s getting what he needs without stressing him out, and the older he gets, the more he’s willing to try a food that is similar to what he’s comfortable with in case he likes it enough to add it to his menu. And we applaud his bravery every time.

He’s almost 16, and we’ll still get comments and suggestions from people who mean well, but can’t seem to wrap their heads around the fact that he knows what he’s good with eating, and we’re good with letting him make those choices.

When we’ve gone out as a family to eat, there’s a difference in his enjoyment level if the server goes with the flow when he orders or makes a comment of “I don’t think your mom and dad will be ok with that”. His relief with the first and stress with the second is palpable.

But at my dad’s house, he gets quiet and tense. His whole body is rigid, because he’s waiting for the inevitable “Are you sure you don’t want to try _____ ? I bet you’d like it if you gave it a chance.” He doesn’t talk to anyone and he retreats into himself until we leave.

My mom’s house, my MiL’s, my brother’s - he’s comfortable there. Relaxed and as sociable as he gets with other people, sharing trivia or hanging out calmly in a quiet area. He knows they all all respect his food choices. There’s no questions or expectations.

It’s hard having a child with food sensitivities, because you always worry if they are getting enough of what they need to be healthy while they grow. But there’s a visible difference in his entire demeanor when we eat somewhere and he’s unsure how people will act.

When Dude was a toddler, we were encouraged to do occupational therapy to help him “overcome” his food sensitivities before it was “too late”. $6k and 6 months later we stopped, because I could see how traumatizing it was for him. I couldn’t do that to him anymore. https://t.co/Zd9vNHvfYD

2020 has been a flaming dumpster fire for my brain, and that took its toll on pretty much every area of my life. But I’m seeing small lights in the darkness now, and I’m going to try to have more stability in 2021. Fingers crossed.

Getting my adhd diagnosis helped the process a lot. Understanding my brain has been hugely beneficial to accepting my body’s limits. I still get frustrated and feel guilty, but it’s not nearly as intense as it used to be.

I don’t know if I’m a spoonie, or if I’m just dealing with the consequences of years spent being mostly sedentary, but I think I’ve hit a point where I’m coming to terms with my limitations, and trying to work within them instead of wallowing.

Attempting to go into the new year with the kind of energy I hope to have all year long, so I’m using this week as a practice run. Yesterday I knocked physical chores off my to do list, so today I’m doing planning/scheduling so my body can take a break. Baby steps.

Where food/meals used to be an area full of tension, now it’s just fun. (For the most part. Kids are never predictable.) So. If any of you are dealing with power struggles over food, find what works best for you and your family, and throw the Rule Book in the trash.

Examples: they order the zippoli at Olive Garden while simultaneously devouring basket after basket of breadsticks. Or they ask for “lots and lots” of rolls from Texas Roadhouse. We get looks ranging from curious to judgmental, but they eat until they’re full, like anyone else.

They have gotten more adventurous (for them, anyway) as they’ve gotten older, thankfully, but for a while their menus were pretty limited. It always amuses me when we take them to restaurants with us, though. Servers never know how to respond to what we let them order.

And it was around that time that Diva started having issues with food and texture too, so then it was a losing battle. I wasn’t going to have 2 different sets of rules, so this is just how it is at our house. Makes for weird family dinners, but who needs normal anyway?

We did occupational therapy with Dude when he was 3-4 and all it caused was stress, sadness, and a bill for $6000. Then we tried the “you eat what we eat or nothing” and it caused other problems. So one day I just said to myself “it is what it is.”

I relate to this thread quite a bit. Dude has major food texture sensitivities and Diva has a stronger will than I usually want to go up against, so they eat what they eat. I buy vitamins and encourage them to try what I make, but if they don’t, then that’s ok. https://t.co/umRxLGlHVv

But the reason she’s quiet is because she’s daydreaming. The reason she’s calm is because she’s tired. And the reason she’s respectful is because she’s smart enough to know that’s the best way to fly under a teacher’s radar. A “good” student doesn’t equal an attentive student.

It’s been revealing to have her learning at home though. I can see now why past teachers have looked skeptical when I mentioned she probably has adhd. She’s a “good student” in class. Quiet, calm, and respectful. So they’ve been assuming she’s just fine, and I’m crazy.

Even as a medicated adult, I still have a “this is dumb and I don’t want to deal with it” attitude towards online school. Poor Diva is 11 and (for now) unmedicated, so I’m sure it’s a million times harder for her to feel motivated.

It is both fascinating and heartbreaking helping Diva with school knowing what I know now about adhd. The way we think, and do stuff we don’t like (school), is so similar, it’s crazy. But man I wish Young Jenn had had someone who understood her brain back in school too.

I emailed the principal for Diva’s school and Dude’s assigned special ed teacher asking for information about the coming school year and advice on how the online district options work for kids with IEPs. Their responses were so different, I almost had to laugh.
It will never cease to amaze me the difference in helpfulness for special education kids from the administrations/teachers in elementary vs junior and senior high.

These are COLLEGE STUDENTS. Not teenagers. I am all for colleges protecting the students from harassment and assault, but it shouldn’t be their place to essentially try to be the parent over students’ behavior.

My childhood was run this way. You aren’t taught how and why to make choices that are good for you, you’re taught to be afraid of punishment for not following a strict rule book. But then you become an adult and have no experience in using your own moral compass.
